===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|ideæ}}

# {{context|philosophy|lang=en}} An abstract [[archetype]] of a given thing, compared to which real-life examples are seen as imperfect [[approximation]]s; pure [[essence]], as opposed to actual examples. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2013-10-19|volume=409|issue=8858|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21588115-younger-generation-emerges-aung-san-suu-kyis-shadow-and-tries-turn-her-party Trouble at the lab]
|passage=The '''idea''' that the same experiments always get the same results, no matter who performs them, is one of the cornerstones of science’s claim to objective truth. If a systematic campaign of replication does not lead to the same results, then either the original research is flawed (as the replicators claim) or the replications are (as many of the original researchers on priming contend). Either way, something is awry.}}
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The conception of someone or something as representing a perfect [[example]]; an [[ideal]]. {{defdate|16th-19th c.}}
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The [[form]] or [[shape]] of something; a quintessential [[aspect]] or [[characteristic]]. {{defdate|16th-18th c.}}
#* '''1603''', {{w|John Florio}}, translating {{w|Michel de Montaigne}}, ''Essays'', II.6:
#*: The remembrance whereof (which yet I beare deepely imprinted in my minde) representing me her visage and '''''Idea''''' so lively and so naturally, doth in some sort reconcile me unto her.
# An [[image]] of an object that is formed in the mind or recalled by the memory. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: {{usex|The mere '''idea''' of you is enough to excite me.|lang=en}}
# More generally, any result of mental activity; a [[thought]], a [[notion]]; a way of thinking. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=3
|passage=Now all this was very fine, but not at all in keeping with the Celebrity's character as I had come to conceive it. The '''idea''' that adulation ever cloyed on him was ludicrous in itself. In fact I thought the whole story fishy, and came very near to saying so.}}
#* '''1952''', {{w|Alfred Whitney Griswold}}
#*: '''Ideas''' won't go to jail.
# A conception in the mind of something to be done; a [[plan]] for doing something, an {{l|en|intention}}. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{usex|I have an '''idea''' of how we might escape.|lang=en}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1913|author={{w|Joseph C. Lincoln}}|chapter=3
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=My hopes wa'n't disappointed. I never saw clams thicker than they was along them inshore flats. I filled my dreener in no time, and then it come to me that 'twouldn't be a bad '''idee''' to get a lot more, take 'em with me to Wellmouth, and peddle 'em out. Clams was fairly scarce over that side of the bay and ought to fetch a fair price.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2013-06-01|volume=407|issue=8838|page=71|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21578670-peer-peer-lending-needs-new-name-end-peer-show End of the peer show]
|passage=Finance is seldom romantic. But the '''idea''' of peer-to-peer lending comes close. This is an industry that brings together individual savers and lenders on online platforms. Those that want to borrow are matched with those that want to lend.}}
# A vague or fanciful {{l|en|notion}}; a [[feeling]] or [[hunch]]; an [[impression]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{usex|He had the wild '''idea''' that if he leant forward a little, he might be able to touch the mountain-top.|lang=en}}
# {{context|music|lang=en}} A [[musical]] [[theme]] or [[melodic]] [[subject]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}

